{"questionId":"27763","questionHtml":"<p>The sum of the first <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> square numbers can be expressed as a cubic polynomial with three terms:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:90px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mo largeop=\"true\">Σ</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℚ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>\n<p>Hence, write down a system of three linear equations in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>27</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> For the third <em><strong>A</strong></em> mark, award <em><strong>A1FT</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>27</mn><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math> is their answer to part (b) (i).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27763","referenceCode":"22N.3.AHL.TZ0.1b.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The sum of the first n square numbers can be expressed as a cubic polynomial with three terms: Σi=1ni2=a1n+a2n2+a3n3 where a1, a2, a3∈ℚ+. Hence, write down a system of three linear","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"b.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.16—Solution of systems of linear equations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}